TASK_DESCRIPTION=CRITICAL SCOPE CORRECTION on parent #439. The existing implementation (shell/intent-fallback.sh via Haiku) is built as a typo corrector — it matches misspellings to known commands. USER CLARIFIED THE REAL INTENT: it must be a full natural-language command router that understands intent from ANY phrasing, not just typos, and resolves arguments by querying doey state.

User's example: 'doey start <project> please' -> must (a) recognize start-project intent, (b) find the actual project by name/fuzzy match against a project registry, (c) invoke 'doey' in that project directory. The 'please' is irrelevant, the project name needs resolution, and there's no typo to correct.

More examples (behavior spec):
- 'doey start my-site please' -> find my-site project, cd there, launch doey
- 'doey show me what is running' -> doey task list OR doey status team
- 'doey kill everything' -> doey kill-all-sessions (PROMPT because destructive)
- 'doey open the dashboard' -> attach to window 0 of current session
- 'doey i wanna work on frontend' -> resolve frontend project, launch
- 'doey tsk lst' (old typo case) -> still works, as a trivial subset

WHAT NEEDS TO CHANGE (design):

1. Command schema dump for Haiku/Sonnet. Every subcommand + args + purpose, machine-readable, fed into the prompt as the action vocabulary. Source of truth = auto-generated from doey.sh help or a new doey-ctl schema command. Must stay in sync automatically (not hand-maintained).

2. Project registry. doey needs to know what projects exist. Options to evaluate:
   a) Config file user populates: ~/.config/doey/projects.yaml
   b) Auto-discovery: scan ~/code ~/projects ~/src ~/Github ~/GitHub for git repos, cache
   c) Recent-projects tracking: every doey launch records cwd to ~/.config/doey/recent-projects
   d) Hybrid — auto-discovery + recent + manual overrides
   Recommend (d). Registry feeds Haiku with a candidate list so it can match names.

3. Context data injected into the prompt: current session, running teams, recent projects, pwd, tailnet hostname, etc. So the model can resolve 'here', 'this session', 'the frontend', etc.

4. Execution surface. Not just 'run command X'. Must be able to pass RESOLVED arguments. Output JSON contract from model:
   { "action": "start_project", "args": { "path": "/home/doey/projects/my-site" }, "confidence": 0.92, "explanation": "...", "destructive": false }
   Dispatcher then maps action -> real doey command with resolved args.

5. Confidence tiers:
   - >=0.85 and non-destructive -> auto-execute, print what's being run
   - 0.60-0.85 OR destructive -> print 'Will run: <command>' and require [y/N]
   - <0.60 -> print top 3 guesses as suggestions, do not execute

6. Model selection. Haiku may be insufficient for argument resolution + fuzzy project matching. Evaluate: Haiku for pure command routing (fast path), escalate to Sonnet when action requires argument resolution. Or always use Sonnet for simplicity and accept ~2s latency on the error path.

7. Destructive action list must be explicit (kill-all-sessions, stop, reset, uninstall, rm, trash, etc.) — model-reported 'destructive' flag is advisory, not authoritative.

8. Fallback chain when claude binary missing or API key absent: degrade to current hard error, NOT crash. Zero regression.

9. Existing shell/intent-fallback.sh + shell/doey-intent-dispatch.sh must be reused where possible, rewritten where scope demands. Keep opt-out DOEY_NO_INTENT_FALLBACK=1 working.

10. Wire it in. The current implementation is NOT called from shell/doey.sh unknown-command handler (verified live: 'doey tsk lst' returns raw Unknown command, no log file written). Root-cause and fix the wiring FIRST, then extend scope — otherwise the scope extension won't land either.

PHASES:
- Phase 1 (immediate): Fix the wiring bug so the current narrow typo-corrector at least runs. Prove end-to-end: 'doey tsk lst' -> suggestion -> execution -> log file exists.
- Phase 2 (this task): Scope expansion per above. Schema dump, project registry (recent + auto-discovery), context injection, JSON action contract, confidence tiers, destructive guard.
- Phase 3: Acceptance test suite covering 10+ real-world phrasings. Every phrasing must be runnable from a test script with mock claude -p where needed.

FRESH-INSTALL: must work after curl | bash. No API key -> hard-fail with current behavior. claude binary missing -> same. All new files ship via install.sh.

USER IS FRUSTRATED with the 'ship sweep passed but happy path was never tested' pattern. Acceptance criteria for this task includes a live end-to-end demo: run 'doey start <real-project> please' and show it actually launches doey in that project dir.
TASK_SUBTASKS=1:Phase 1: Fix wiring bug so current intent-fallback.sh actually runs from doey.sh unknown-command handler. End-to-end validation required. IN-FLIGHT as 439 subtask 478419 on W3.1.:done\n2:Phase 2: Scope expansion design. Command schema dump (auto-generated from doey.sh), project registry (hybrid auto-discover + recent + manual), context injection, JSON action contract {action,args,confidence,explanation,destructive}, confidence tiers (>=0.85 auto, 0.60-0.85 or destructive confirm, <0.60 suggest).:done\n3:Phase 2: Implementation. Rewrite shell/intent-fallback.sh + shell/doey-intent-dispatch.sh per expanded scope. Reuse where possible. Opt-out DOEY_NO_INTENT_FALLBACK=1 preserved.:done\n4:Phase 3: Acceptance test suite — 10+ real-world phrasings with mock claude -p. Live end-to-end demo: 'doey start <real-project> please' launches doey in project dir.:done\n5:Fresh-install verification: install.sh copies all new files; doey doctor passes; no API key / no claude binary -> graceful hard-fail with current behavior (zero regression).:done
